Thom Wiggers said:

@Jonathan: that already is true for client authentication in the regular handshake, because client auth succeeding or failing has no effect on the keys and is not notified to the client (if the server continues after failure)

I'll have to read the section of the paper again, but we talk about it at length in section 5.2.

@Alicja Kario 

@Mike server side: just deploy a single certificate that has multiple identities in it

I'm constructing a straw-man on-the-fly, but I think the counter-example has to do with trust anchors and revocation.
Straw-man: the server needs to assert a machine identity (which chains to some hardware vendor's manufacturing root), and an application identity (let's say a publicly-trusted dNSName cert).
The roots of trust for those two things are very different. It's not clear to me that you can combine those into a single cert from a single root without changing the trust assumptions. Similarly, it's not clear that either of those roots (or any 3rd root) has the authority to revoke. And even if it does, you now have to ask questions about whether the revocation of, say, the dNSName cert will chain properly to the combined cert.
